 {"id":"frankenpandas-989b","title":"fp-conformance: excel_round_trip emits index column by default but reads without index_col","description":"Observed: tests::packet_filter_runs_io_round_trip_packet — 1/10 case fails: excel_round_trip_basic_strict returns actual=false expected=true.

Root: execute_excel_round_trip_fixture_operation (crates/fp-conformance/src/lib.rs:12074) writes via write_excel_bytes (default ExcelWriteOptions{ index: true, ... }, matching pandas) but reads via read_excel_bytes(default ExcelReadOptions, no index_col). Round-trip therefore returns a frame with one extra leading column (the original index), so column_names() diverges and dataframes_semantically_equal returns false.

Fix: write with ExcelWriteOptions{ index: false, ..default }, OR write with index AND read with matching index_col. Simpler & equally valid path: use ExcelWriteOptions { index: false, ..default } in the round-trip helper. Restores parity for excel_round_trip_basic_strict; doesn't touch the public default which must keep index=true to match pandas' to_excel default.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-22T06:30:00.909618976Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-22T06:33:48.386676160Z","closed_at":"2026-04-22T06:33:48.384684809Z","close_reason":"shipped 6468730: switched execute_excel_round_trip_fixture_operation to write_excel_bytes_with_options(index=false) so writer output matches default reader input. packet_filter_runs_io_round_trip_packet now passes 10/10. Public write_excel_bytes default (index=true, pandas-aligned) unchanged. Clippy clean.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
